#Text=Kameʻeiamoku
#Text=Kameʻeiamoku ( died 1802 ) was a Hawaiian high chief and the Counselor of State to King Kamehameha I .
#Text=He was called Kamehameha 's uncle , but he was really the cousin of Kamehameha 's mother , Kekuiapoiwa II .
#Text=Life
#Text=Family
#Text=Along with his twin brother Kamanawa , Kameʻeiamoku 's father was the aliʻi ( Hawaiian nobility ) Keawepoepoe . [ 1 ]
#Text=His mother was Kanoena , also Keawepoepoe 's sister .
#Text=Because their parents were siblings , Kameʻeiamoku and Kamanawa were known as nīʻaupiʻo , the offspring of a royal brother and sister .
#Text=His grandmother was Princess Kalanikauleleiaiwi of Hawaiʻi , who was also the grandmother of Keōua Nui ( Kamehameha 's father ) , making the twins cousins once removed of Kamehameha .

#Text=Kameʻeiamoku was among the first to support Kamehameha I in his rebellion against his cousin Kīwalaʻō ; his fellow supporters were his brother Kamanawa , his half brother Keʻeaumoku Pāpaʻiahiahi , Kamehameha 's warrior teacher Kekūhaupiʻo , and Keawe-a-Heulu .
#Text=These were known as the " five Kona chiefs " .
#Text=Kamehameha took power in the battle of Mokuʻōhai in 1782 , which strengthened his influence .
#Text=In 1790 , the American maritime fur trader Simon Metcalfe of the ship Eleanora mistreated Kameʻeiamoku when he boarded his ship .
#Text=Metcalfe later fired his cannons on the villagers of Olowalu , killing about one hundred .
#Text=In retaliation , Kameʻeiamoku attacked the next American ship to appear , the schooner Fair American , under the command of Thomas Humphrey Metcalfe , the son of Simon Metcalfe .
#Text=All but one of the schooner 's crew was killed , including Thomas Humphrey Metcalfe .
#Text=The lone survivor was Welsh sailor Isaac Davis .
#Text=Another sailor from the Eleanora , Englishman John Young , was sent ashore to find out what happened , and was also captured .
#Text=Davis and Young would both become military advisors and translators for Kamehameha . [ 2 ]
#Text=Kameʻeiamoku participated in negotiating a treaty in February 1795 with George Vancouver for British support of Kamehameha . [ 3 ]
#Text=Kameʻeiamoku had three or four wives and at least three sons .
#Text=His first wife , Kamakaʻeheikuli , was the mother of Kepoʻokalani ( c. 1760 – ? ) who was the double great-grandfather of the last two monarchs of the Kingdom .
#Text=His second wife Kealiʻiokahekili was the mother of Ulumāheihei Hoapili ( c. 1776 – 1840 ) .
#Text=His third wife Kahikoloa was mother of Hoʻolulu ( 1794 – ? ) . [ 4 ] [ 5 ]
#Text=Kameʻeiamoku 's descendants succeeded him in assisting Kamehameha after his death in 1802 in Lahaina on Maui . [ 6 ]
#Text=Legacy
#Text=Through his son Kepoʻokalani came the House of Kalākaua . [ 7 ]
#Text=One of his other sons Hoʻolulu would be the father of Kinoʻole o Liliha who married the notable American businessman Benjamin Pitman .
#Text=Daughter Kekikipaa would marry Kamehameha I , but then marry Keawemauhili and become the mother of High Chiefess Kapiʻolani .
#Text=He lives on the coat of arms of the Kingdom of Hawaii .
#Text=On each side of the coat of arms was the figure of a chief in a feather cloak and a feather helmet .
#Text=The one on the left , bearing a spear , was Kamanawa and the one on the right , with a Kahili ( feather standard ) , was Kameʻeiamoku . [ 8 ]
#Text=The land he was given in 1795 was used by his granddaughter Kuini Liliha , who donated it to Christian missionaries .
#Text=It eventually became Punahou School in 1841 . [ 6 ]
